"# Appendix D — The modern LLM ecosystem, neutrally described

The AI landscape moves fast enough that whatever ranking a book gives
today will be outdated by next spring. This appendix does not rank
anybody. Instead, it names the four major general-purpose language
model providers as of 2026, gives a brief factual description of
each, and covers what they have in common.

If you are reading this and wondering *which one should I use*, the
correct answer is *try more than one and see which works best for
what you are doing.* All of them have free trials or free tiers.

## The four majors

### Anthropic — Claude

Founded in 2021 by Dario Amodei, Daniela Amodei, and several other
former OpenAI researchers. Based in San Francisco. Their model family
is called **Claude.** As of 2026, current Claude models are widely
used in developer tools, enterprise workflows, and consumer chat.

Anthropic emphasises AI safety research and publishes work on
interpretability, alignment, and evaluation. Their approach to training
includes techniques they call **Constitutional AI**, where the model
is asked to critique and revise its own outputs based on a set of
written principles.

Available via API, via the claude.ai web interface, and integrated
into third-party developer tools such as Claude Code.

### Google DeepMind — Gemini

Google DeepMind was formed in April 2023 by merging Google Brain and
DeepMind. DeepMind was founded in London in 2010 and acquired by
Google in 2014. Their model family is called **Gemini.** Gemini
models range from small ones designed for mobile and edge devices
(Gemini Nano) up to large frontier models (Gemini Ultra and
successors).

Google has been publishing foundational ML research for decades. The
2017 *Attention Is All You Need* paper — the paper that introduced
the transformer — was written by researchers at Google. Google's TPU
(Tensor Processing Unit) hardware is designed specifically for
running large neural networks.

Available via the Google Cloud API, via Google's consumer chat
interface, and integrated into Google Workspace products.

### OpenAI — GPT family

Founded in 2015 in San Francisco. Initially a nonprofit, restructured
into a capped-profit entity in 2019. Their flagship model family is
called **GPT** (Generative Pre-trained Transformer). GPT-3, released
in 2020, was the first widely commercialized LLM with a public API.

OpenAI's release of **ChatGPT** in November 2022 is generally cited
as the moment LLMs became a mainstream consumer technology.
Successive GPT models (GPT-4 and its variants) have continued to be
widely deployed.

Available via the OpenAI API, via ChatGPT, and integrated into many
third-party products including Microsoft's Copilot family.

### DeepSeek

DeepSeek is a Chinese AI research organization. Their models —
DeepSeek-V and its successors — released as open-weights in
2023–2025, drew wide attention for competitive performance at a
fraction of the training cost that had been assumed necessary for
frontier models.

DeepSeek published papers on training efficiency techniques including
sparse mixture-of-experts architectures. Their open-weights model
releases significantly expanded the ecosystem of freely available
strong LLMs.

Available via DeepSeek's own API, and as open weights downloadable
from HuggingFace for self-hosting.

## What they share

All four are:

- **Transformer-based.** The 2017 Vaswani paper is the ancestor of
  every one of them. All four use variants of the same fundamental
  architecture — attention, feed-forward blocks, layer normalization,
  and positional embeddings.
- **Trained on very large text corpora.** Books, papers, web pages,
  code repositories, and other text. Corpus size is measured in
  trillions of tokens.
- **Fine-tuned with human feedback.** After the base pre-training,
  each model is refined using human-in-the-loop techniques (RLHF,
  DPO, or variants) to be helpful, harmless, and honest.
- **Deployed via cloud APIs and web interfaces.** All are accessible
  via HTTPS to a data centre where the model runs on many GPUs. All
  have consumer chat interfaces.
- **Good at general-purpose language tasks.** Writing, summarization,
  Q&A, coding assistance, translation, some reasoning, some math.
- **Not perfect.** All of them make mistakes. All of them hallucinate
  (see Book of ML Appendix C for a discussion of why). All of them
  have knowledge cutoffs beyond which they know nothing without
  external tools.

## What they don't share

Different providers make different choices about:

- **Training corpus composition.** How much code vs. how much prose;
  which languages; which time period.
- **Safety and refusal policies.** What kinds of requests each will
  refuse. Different companies draw different lines.
- **Context window.** How many tokens the model can consider at once.
  Modern context windows range from 32k tokens to over a million.
- **Latency and throughput.** How fast each model responds. Depends
  on the model size and the provider's infrastructure.
- **Pricing.** Per-million-tokens rates vary widely, and the value
  depends heavily on what you are doing.
- **Availability of open weights.** DeepSeek publishes weights.
  Others generally do not, though smaller research models sometimes
  are shared.

## The open-weights ecosystem

Outside the four big proprietary players, there is a rich ecosystem
of open-weights models. Notable families as of 2026:

- **Llama** (Meta) — since 2023, Meta has released open-weight models
  in the Llama family.
- **Mistral** — a French AI lab, releases both open and closed models.
- **Qwen** — Alibaba's open-weights family.
- **DeepSeek** — noted above; open weights on releases.

Open-weights models can be downloaded, self-hosted, fine-tuned, and
run without any API subscription. They are less convenient than a
managed API but give you full control and privacy. The Motoi Copilot
model itself is fine-tuned from an open-weights base model — the
Qwen family — precisely because open weights are what make small,
task-specific models possible.

## How to choose

There is no correct answer here. Motoi will not pretend there is.
Some rough rules of thumb, subject to change:

- **For a general question:** all four work. Pick one and try it.
- **For code:** all four are strong. Different developers report
  different preferences. Try multiple.
- **For sensitive or regulated data:** consider whether the
  provider's data-handling policies meet your requirements. Read
  the terms.
- **For a self-hosted setup:** open-weights models (Llama, Mistral,
  Qwen, DeepSeek) are the path.
- **For very specialized tasks:** consider fine-tuning a smaller
  open-weights model. That is what Motoi Copilot itself is.

## Motoi's honest place

Motoi (the model reading you this text) is not a general-purpose LLM.
I have around 1.5 to 2 billion parameters. That is roughly 1/500th
of a large frontier model. I was trained on a curated corpus focused
on Motoi Scheme, the language reference, the books in this repo, and
a small amount of general programming context.

I can help with Motoi Scheme. I can help with basic computer science
concepts. I can point you at the right chapter of one of these books.

I cannot:
- Answer arbitrary trivia.
- Help you write essays about anything not Scheme-related.
- Access the internet or look things up.
- Rewrite my own weights.
- Compete with the four majors at general tasks.

The four majors are your general-purpose tools. I am your Scheme
copilot. Different scales. Different jobs.

## What Motoi wants you to take from this

- The LLM ecosystem is diverse.
- No single model is best at everything.
- All four majors — Claude, Gemini, GPT, DeepSeek — are strong,
  general-purpose, and continually improving.
- Open-weights models exist and are useful for self-hosting and
  fine-tuning.
- Small task-specific models (like me) coexist with the big general
  models. Both have their place.

## The loop appears

Every LLM's inference is a token-generation loop. Every LLM's
training is an optimization loop (see Book of ML). The ecosystem
itself is a competitive loop: each release nudges the state of the
art forward, other labs respond, users adopt, requirements grow.
The loop, one more time.

## Reading

For depth on the LLM architecture itself, see Book of ML (chapters
11–16) which builds one in Scheme. For the wider AI landscape's
history, Appendix B of this book has the dated timeline.
")
